  "prompt": "In movies that play in the US, tires of cars are always squeaking. Why?",
  "response": "The squeaking or screeching sound of tires in movies serves several purposes. \n\n1. **Dramatic Effect**: The sound enhances the drama and tension of a scene, especially during car chases or high-speed pursuits. Adding squeaking tires can heighten the intensity and make the action feel more urgent and exciting.\n\n2. **Realism**: In real life, tires often make noise when they are turning sharply or skidding. Including this sound in films adds a layer of realism, as it mimics what audiences would expect to hear in those situations.\n\n3. **Sound Design**: Filmmakers and sound designers create an auditory experience that engages viewers. The sound of squeaking tires can be used strategically to draw attention to a specific moment or action within a scene.\n\n4. **Cinematic Convention**: Over time, certain sounds have become stereotypes or conventions in filmmaking. The sound of squeaky tires has become a familiar auditory cue that audiences associate with speed, danger, or excitement.\n\nUltimately, the use of squeaking tires in films is a combination of artistic choice, audience engagement, and the desire to convey certain emotions and reactions effectively.",
